article.headline: UConn bounces back after collapse vs. Rutgers
article.linkText: Win over ND helps UConn's mindset
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The regular season finale for Connecticut
haunted the Huskies all week.

Losing an 18-point lead, eventual game and a share of the
regular season title to Rutgers last week became the rallying point
to prepare for the Big East tournament. But before they could get
their game right, the Huskies needed to get their heads right.

They responded Sunday night with a 71-60 win over Notre Dame in
the tournament quarterfinal.

Barbara Turner led a determined UConn squad with 19 points and
Ketia Swanier added a career-high 11 to lead the seventh-ranked
Huskies. Ann Strother finished with 10 for No. 7 UConn.

"I'm a senior now and I have the right idea of the type of
mindset you have to have," Turner said.

The second-seeded Huskies (27-4) advance to play DePaul, which
beat Pittsburgh 69-46.

"We needed some time," UConn coach Geno Auriemma said. "The
only days we did anything was Friday and Saturday. Both of the days
were more of just getting our heads rather than our bodies ready.
We had a talk last night with the team and a lot of really good
things came out."

The five-time national champions have dominated this tournament
as they aim for their 13th tournament title. They've lost the last
two regular season crowns to Rutgers, but somehow have found a way
to rebound in the Big East championship.

Willnett Crockett had a team-high 11 boards for UConn, which
finished with a 36-23 advantage on the glass and outscored the
10th-seeded Irish 34-20 in the paint. The Huskies' 27 defensive
rebounds afforded the Irish few second chances and helped UConn get
out in transition quickly. Guards Renee Mongtomery and Swanier
directed UConn's uptempo attack with a combined 10 assists as the
Huskies shot 58 percent from the floor.

Crockett said the team was eager to get back on the court after
the collapse at Rutgers.

"In practice the whole week we were just harping on what we had
to do after losing to a team like Rutgers," Crockett said. "We
were all pretty much focused on getting her and getting the job
done."

Notre Dame coach Muffett McGraw said the Irish tried to keep
Strother, a 3-point specialist, from getting open outside looks.
Turner picked up the slack. In her ninth tournament game, the
senior forward's 19 points were a tournament high for her.

"I'm a senior now and I have the right idea of the type of
mindset you have to have," Turner said.

Notre Dame's Megan Duffy had 14 of her team-high 20 points in
the final 10 minutes of the game as the Fighting Irish tried to
rally from 21 down.

Courtney LeVere finished with 15 points and two blocked shots
for the Irish. Despite early foul trouble, LeVere stayed on the
floor to try and kick start the offense.

"We weren't getting enough offense without her," McGraw said.
"She's smart enough to play with two fouls."

The Huskies relied on their post game early to take control.
Fifteen of their 19 first-half boards were on the defensive end
resulted in several breakaway layups.

Turner and Charde Houston muscled their way inside for two
layups in a 9-0 UConn run. Turner capped the spurt with an
up-and-under around 6-foot-5 Melissa D'Amico with 10:38 left in the
period for an 18-11 lead.

The Huskies led by as many as 18 in the period and led 38-24 at
the break. UConn stretched the lead to 21 in the first five minutes
of the second half. The Irish would get no closer than 11 the rest
of the way, despite Duffy's efforts. And Connecticut had a reason
to be concerned.

Duffy rallied the Irish the night before, getting all 16 of her
points in the second half in Notre Dame's 73-66 win over South
Florida in a first-round game.

"(Duffy) should get 40 points if she played the way she did in
the last 10 minutes," Auriemma said. "She's just one of those
unselfish kids who wants to get the other people on her team the
ball. She showed in the last 10 minutes how hard she is to
defend."
